1. Create and Write

Action: Create a new file in VS Code with the .s extension (e.g., test.s).

Note: This is where you write your human-readable assembly instructions.

2. Save (Critical)

Action: Save the file in VS Code (Cmd + S).

Reason: Docker is looking at the file on your hard drive. If you don't save, Docker will try to assemble the old version (or an empty file).

3. Assemble (NASM)

Action: Convert the text file into a machine-readable Object File.

Command: nasm -f elf -o [object_name].o [source_name].s

Example: nasm -f elf -o main.o test.s

Terminology: The .o file is the "Object" file. It contains binary code but isn't a finished program yet.

4. Link (LD)

Action: Link the object file to the Linux system to create the final Executable.

Command: ld -m elf_i386 -o [program_name] [object_name].o

Example: ld -m elf_i386 -o my_program main.o

Requirement: The -m elf_i386 flag is mandatory because you are compiling 32-bit code on a 64-bit system.

5. Execute

Action: Run the finished program.

Command: ./[program_name]

Example: ./my_program

Full Workflow Example

If your file is named lab1.s, you would run these three lines in order:

nasm -f elf -o lab1.o lab1.s

ld -m elf_i386 -o lab1_exec lab1.o

./lab1_exec


OR: 
# 1. Assemble with Debug Symbols (-g)
nasm -f elf -g -o working.o working_with_bytes_and_stuff.s

# 2. Link for 32-bit Linux
ld -m elf_i386 -o working_app working.o

# 3. Dump with Source (-S) and Intel syntax (-M intel)
objdump -S -M intel working_app